<section xml:id="sec_Gerrymandering">
  <title>Gerrymandering</title>
  <p>
        <idx><h>gerrymander</h></idx>
  </p>
  <tabular xml:id="fig_gerrymander">
    {m{.45\textwidth}m{.45\textwidth}}
    The process of dividing the state into the appropriate number of districts is called redistricting, but in the popular press, it is often referred to as gerrymandering.  This is because the map-makers often decide to split things up to their benefit.  One of the earliest, most obvious examples of this was in 1812 when Massachusetts Governor Gerry and his party drew one district in such a curvy and jagged manner that the local press thought it looked like a Salamander (see <xref ref="fig_gerrymander">Figure</xref>) and coined the term Gerrymander. &amp;
    <image width="50%" source="images/gerrymander.png"/>
  </tabular>
