      The last diagram is an example of the <sq>packing</sq> and <sq>cracking</sq> that are illustrative of modern gerrymandering.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <title>packing</title>
          <p>
            Putting a very large number of voters who all vote the same way in a single district.
            In this case, the election is won by these voters,
            but by a very large margin.
              <idx><h>gerrymander</h><h>packing</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>cracking</title>
          <p>
            Putting a slight majority of voters for one party in a single district.
            In this case,
            the election is won by these voters by a slim margin.
            There are a lot of minority voters in the district,
            but not enough to ever win an election.
              <idx><h>gerrymander</h><h>cracking</h></idx>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
